OCDST: Offloading Chained DNNs for Streaming Tasks

 

Chained DNN

Chained DNNs refer to the DNNs with directional chain relationship between layers, where there might be some circular connections and shortcuts. Fig. 1, 2, 3 show the standard form, chained form of AlexNet and a general chained DNN, respectively.

Fig. 1. The Standard Form of AlexNet

Fig. 2. The Chained Form of AlexNet

Fig. 3. A General Chained DNN

 

Streaming Tasks

Streaming tasks refer to the tasks continuously published by a task source. Generally, the publishing rate of a task stream is high, and tasks need the same executing procedure. We focus on a special kind of streaming tasks where some tasks are allowed lost as long as the overall streaming requirements are met.

Task publishment can be regarded as a transmission procedure. If the task source is on a computing unit, tasks will be transmitted from the publishing program to the executing program. Otherwise, tasks will be transmitted from the publishing unit to the computing unit. Suppose that task publishment and execution are carried out in parallel, and a task starts to be executed after it is transmitted. Since the tasks need the same executing procedure, their executing delays will be the same with the same computing power. An instance of task publishment and execution is plotted as a Gantt chart, as shown in Fig. 4. The executing procedure starts after the publishment of task ①, and the publishment of subsequent tasks is not affected by the execution. In this case, the executing delay is greater than the publishing delay so that the publishment of tasks ③ and ④ are completed during the execution of task ②. To provide users with real-time response, the executor discards task ③ and continues executing from task ④.

Fig. 4. Tasks' Publishment and Execution

 

System Model

For an n-layer DNN, let C={c1,c2,...,cn} represent its computing amount (floating-point operations, FLOPs) of each layer, and S={s1,s2,...,sn} represent the size (Mbytes) of the output data. Besides, suppose that there are m computing units, where Vc={v1c,v2c,…,vmc}, Vut={vu,1t,vu,2t,…,vu,mt} and Vdt={vd,1t,vd,2t,…,vd,mt} respectively represent the computing speed (floating-point operations per second, FLOPS), upload bandwidth (Mbytes/s) and download bandwidth (Mbytes/s) of them, then the computing time of the ith layer at the jth computing unit is

ti,jc=civjc

The transmission time of the output of the ith DNN layer from the kth computing unit to the lth unit is

ti,j,kt=simin(vu,kt,vd,lt)

Indicating whether the ith DNN layer is offloaded to the kth unit with the element pki of a binary matrix P, simplifying P as P=[p1,p2,...,pm], where pk=[pk1,pk2,...,pkn]T merely indicates the status of the computing unit k, and denoting the time computing each DNN layer at the kth unit as a vector tkc=[t1,kc,t2,kc,...,tn,kc]T, then the computing delay of unit k is

Tkc=pk⋅tkc

Let the element eji of a binary matrix E denotes whether the ith layer is directly connected to the jth layer. Then the publishing and receiving delays of the kth unit are

Tkp=∑i=1n∑j=1n∑k=1m∑l=1mpkipljejiti,k,lt

and

Tkp=∑i=1n∑j=1n∑k=1m∑l=1mpkipijeijtj,l,kt

respectively, then we can model the DNN offloading as

minmax1≤k≤m(Tk)s.t.Tk=max{Tkr,Tkc,Tkp}∑k=1mpki=1,∀i∈[1,n]eji=0,∀i>jei+1i=1,∀i∈[1,n−1]
